N2  - Peer review of economic policies by countries comprises peer learning, peer support and peer pressure. Durable peer review processes focus on mutual peer learning and support as peer pressure rarely works unless countries can be convinced that a policy is in their national interest. It requires a high degree of trust and respect, sharing of information, analytical and administrative capacity and legitimacy. Proximity may lead to greater trust and openness, but it may also be associated with long-standing historical differences and grievances. In principle peer review could be a useful adjunct to other aspects of a regional integration strategy designed to bring mutual benefit to the participating countries. In the Asian context there appears ample scope for well designed peer review to contribute to domestic policy development.
